field, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1302–1353":"1302–1353","1304–1334":"1304–1334","1328–Female":"1328–Overleden","1307–1367":"1307–1367","1285–1333":"1285–1333","1285–1345":"1285–1345","1327":"1327","1304":"1304","1302":"1302","Abt 1333":"circa 1333","1345":"1345","1367":"1367","1334":"1334","1333":"1333","1353":"1353","1285":"1285","1307":"1307","1328":"1328","Wigan, Lancashire, England":"Wigan, Lancashire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Wigan, , Lancashire, England":"Wigan, Lancashire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Ince-in-Makerfield, Lancashire, England":"Ince-in-Makerfield, Lancashire, England","Ince, Ashton-in-Makerfield, Merseyside, England, United Kingdom":"Ince, Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Ince Manor, Lancashire, England":"Ince-in-Makerfield, Lancashire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1302–1353":"1302–1353","1304–1334":"1304–1334","1328–Female":"1328–Deceased","1307–1367":"1307–1367","1285–1333":"1285–1333","1285–1345":"1285–1345","1327":"1327","1304":"1304","1302":"1302","Abt 1333":"about 1333","1345":"1345","1367":"1367","1334":"1334","1333":"1333","1353":"1353","1285":"1285","1307":"1307","1328":"1328","Wigan, Lancashire, England":"Wigan, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Wigan, , Lancashire, England":"Wigan, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Ince-in-Makerfield, Lancashire, England":"Ince-in-Makerfield, Lancashire, England","Ince, Ashton-in-Makerfield, Merseyside, England, United Kingdom":"Ince, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Ince Manor, Lancashire, England":"Ince-in-Makerfield, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Ince","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["habitational name from Ince in Makerfield (Lancashire), Ince (Cheshire), or Ince Blundell (Lancashire). The placenames derive from Proto-Welsh <i>ïnïs</i> ‘island’.","possibly a post-medieval West Midlands variant of <b>Hints</b>, a habitational name from either of two places called Hints (Staffordshire, Shropshire). The placenames probably derive from Proto-Welsh <i>hïnt</i> ‘way, path’ + Middle English plural <i>-es</i>.","possibly a variant with plural or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i> of <i>Inn</i>, from residence at an <i>inn</i> or <i>inns</i>, from Middle English <i>in</i> (singular) or <i>innes</i> (plural) ‘tavern, lodging(s), tenement(s)’. There seems also to have been some confusion with Scottish   Innes  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Hince","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Michel.","English: variant of   Ince  .","Altered form of English   Hains  ."]},{"name":"Ence","meanings":["English: variant of   Ince  .","Americanized form of South German   Enz  , a short form of   Anselm  .","History: Two brothers, Johannes and Gottlieb Enz, immigrated from northern Switzerland to southern Utah around 1860. Their descendants bear the surname <i>Ence</i>."]},{"name":"Innes","meanings":["Scottish: shortened form of   McInnis  , from Gaelic <b>Mag Aonghuis</b> ‘son of Aonghus’.","Scottish: habitational name from the barony of Innes in Urquhart (Morayshire), named from Gaelic <i>inis</i> ‘island’.","English: variant of   Ince  ."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Richard Ince was born in 1302, in Wigan, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Richard Ince, was 18 and his mother, Elizabeth Radcliffe, was 17. He married Helen Ince in 1327, in Wigan, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1353, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 51."},"et":{"1302–1353":"1302–1353","1304–1334":"1304–1334","1328–Female":"1328–Surnud","1307–1367":"1307–1367","1285–1333":"1285–1333","1285–1345":"1285–1345","1327":"1327","1304":"1304","1302":"1302","Abt 1333":"umbes 1333","1345":"1345","1367":"1367","1334":"1334","1333":"1333","1353":"1353","1285":"1285","1307":"1307","1328":"1328","Wigan, Lancashire, England":"Wigan, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Wigan, , Lancashire, England":"Wigan, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Ince-in-Makerfield, Lancashire, England":"Ince-in-Makerfield, Lancashire, England","Ince, Ashton-in-Makerfield, Merseyside, England, United Kingdom":"Ince, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Ince Manor, Lancashire, England":"Ince-in-Makerfield, Lancashire, Inglismaa, Uni